### CHAPTER XIII.

0\. The signification of the Gâthas <span
id="fr_1760"></span>[9](#fn_1748.md).

1\. These three Ashem-vohûs (Yas. XI, end) which

<span id="page_353">p. 353</span>

*represent* <span id="fr_1761"></span>[1](#fn_1749.md) the Fravarânê (Yas.
XI, end) of the preliminary ritual (pê*s* nîrang) and the rotation of
these three Hâs ('chapters'), the Fravarânê, Frastuyê, and
Âstuyê—fravarânê *being* the beginning of the Fravarânê <span
id="fr_1762"></span>[2](#fn_1750.md) *which extends* as far as
frasastayaê*k*a <span id="fr_1763"></span>[3](#fn_1751.md), frastuyê <span
id="fr_1764"></span>[4](#fn_1752.md), the beginning of the Frastuyê (Yas.
XII, I-XIII, 26) *which extends* up to the Âstuyê, and âstuyê <span
id="fr_1765"></span>[5](#fn_1753.md), the beginning of the
Âstaothwanem <span id="fr_1766"></span>[6](#fn_1754.md), (Yas. XIII,
27-XIV, end) *which extends* as far as âstaothwanem*k*â daênay*a*u
Mâzdayasnôi*s*—*also represent* the Vîsâi-v*e*-ameshâ-spe*n*tâ (Yas.
XV), *which is* the beginning of the Stôtânyasnô ('the ritual of
praisers') <span id="fr_1767"></span>[7](#fn_1755.md), and these three Hâs
of the Baghãm (Yas. XIX-XXI).

2\. In the exposition (*k*ashî*d*ak) and through the

<span id="page_354">p. 354</span>

evidence of revelation (dînô) the wise of those of the primitive
faith <span id="fr_1768"></span>[1](#fn_1756.md) *have* thus said, that a
man of fifteen years <span id="fr_1769"></span>[2](#fn_1757.md), and a son
and, brother of Mazdayasnians—when he confesses *his* failings (mândak)
to the high-priests (ra*d*ân), and they shall bring him the whip and
scourge <span id="fr_1770"></span>[3](#fn_1758.md), and these five
Gâthas <span id="fr_1771"></span>[4](#fn_1759.md) are chanted and the good
waters consecrated by him, and the whole of the renewed-birth *ceremony*
(navî*d*-zâ*d*îh) <span id="fr_1772"></span>[5](#fn_1760.md) is performed
by him—*becomes* a mature youth and not a child, and a share of the
prayers of initiation (nâpar) and of the fires is to be given over to
him <span id="fr_1773"></span>[6](#fn_1761.md); and when thus much is not
performed by him, a share is not to be given. 3. These five <span
id="fr_1774"></span>[7](#fn_1762.md) Gâthas are made up from the body of a
righteous man.

<span id="page_355">p. 355</span>

4\. Ahyâ-yâsâ (Yas. XXVIII), Khshmaibyâ (Yas. XXIX), and A*d*-tâ-vakhshâ
(Yas. XXX) *have*, severally, eleven stanzas (va*k*êst), because eleven
things move spiritually within the bodies of men, as life,
consciousness, religion, soul, guardian spirit, thought, word, deed,
seeing, smelling, and hearing; and the bodies of men and other creatures
are formed of water, fire, and wind <span
id="fr_1775"></span>[1](#fn_1763.md).

5\. Ashem-Ahurem-mazdãm (Visp. XV) is *to be recited* <span
id="fr_1776"></span>[2](#fn_1764.md) three times before the coming of
Hûshê*d*ar, Hûshê*d*ar-mâh, and Sôshyans; and when they also recite the
chapter (hâ*d*) well, and by line (gâs) and stanza, those *apostles* are
present <span id="fr_1777"></span>[3](#fn_1765.md), and the

<span id="page_356">p. 356</span>

country becomes more flourishing and more dominant in the world.

6\. The twenty-two stanzas of Tâ-v*e*-urvâtâ (Yas. XXXI) are the
twenty-two judgments (dâ*d*istân) of which it speaks in the Hâ*d*ôkht
*Nask* <span id="fr_1778"></span>[1](#fn_1766.md) thus:—'Anaomô mananghê
daya vîspâi kva, kva parô?' (where are *they* to be produced beyond
every thought? *and* where before?') 'Lodging in the judge, that while
*he has* twenty-two judgments *he may be* more just;'—so that when they
pray the Tâ-v*e*-urvâtâ chapter well, and recite *it* by line and
stanza, the judges possess those twenty-two judgments more correctly,
and judiciousness is more lodging *in them*.

7\. The sixteen stanzas of the *Hv*aêtumaithi *chapter* (Yas.
XXXII) <span id="fr_1779"></span>[2](#fn_1767.md) are lodging in warriors,
so that it becomes possible, during their good protection, to force the
enemy *away* from those sixteen countries which the Vendidad <span
id="fr_1780"></span>[3](#fn_1768.md) mentions in *its* first fargar*d*.

<span id="page_357">p. 357</span>

8\. The fourteen stanzas of Yathâ-âi*s* (Yas. XXXIII) are for this
reason, because seven archangels are more diligent in activity *for* the
spirit, and seven archangels <span id="fr_1781"></span>[1](#fn_1769.md) for
the world, so that they may attain 'to heaven, the home (mêhônŏ) of
Aûharmazd, the home of the archangels, the home of those righteous
ones,' avi garô-nmânem, maêthanem Ahurahê mazd*a*u, maêthanem ameshanãm
spe*n*tanãm, maêthanem anyaêshãm ashaonãm <span
id="fr_1782"></span>[2](#fn_1770). 9. The three repetitions (dânar.md) of
Y*e*-s*e*vi*s*tô (Yas. XXXIII, 11) <span
id="fr_1783"></span>[3](#fn_1771.md), *and* the holding up of the
holy-water (zôhar) at these *repetitions*, are for the four
classes <span id="fr_1784"></span>[4](#fn_1772.md), and for this *reason*
at Ahurâi mazdâi *and* ashem*k*â frâda*d* <span
id="fr_1785"></span>[5](#fn_1773.md) the holy-water is

<span id="page_358">p. 358</span>

to be held level with the heart of him who is the officiating priest
(zôt), and at sraotâ <span id="fr_1786"></span>[1](#fn_1774.md) *it* is to
be held level with the arm of him who is the officiating priest, so that
while the warriors are in battle with foreigners (anâîrân) they may be
fuller of breath (vayô-gîrtar), and the husbandmen stronger-armed in the
tillage and cultivation of the world.

10\. The fifteen stanzas of Yâ-*s*kyaothanâ (Yas. XXXIV) are for this
reason, because it is given <span id="fr_1787"></span>[2](#fn_1775.md) for
the destruction of those fifteen fiends who are disclosed in the medical
part (bêshâ*z*) of the Hâ*d*ôkht *Nask* <span
id="fr_1788"></span>[3](#fn_1776). 11. The four repetitions (bâr.md) of
Mazdâ-a*d*-môi (Yas. XXXIV, 15) <span id="fr_1789"></span>[4](#fn_1777.md)
are for the right coming on of the share of these five chieftainships
(ra*d*îh), the house-ruler, the village-ruler, the tribe-ruler, the
province-ruler, and the supreme Zaratû*s*t <span
id="fr_1790"></span>[5](#fn_1778.md).

12\. The two repetitions of Ahyâ-yâsâ (Yas. XVIII, 1) <span
id="fr_1791"></span>[6](#fn_1779.md), are for this reason, that the
sovereign (dahyûpat) may not at once seize body, consciousness,

<span id="page_359">p. 359</span>

and soul. 13. Those four Yathâ-ahû-vairyôs of the first *Gâtha* <span
id="fr_1792"></span>[1](#fn_1780.md) are for this reason, that is, so that
inferiors may become more tolerant of the commands of superiors, and
good thoughts, good words, and good deeds be more domesticated
(mâhmântar) in the world, and the fiend more powerless
(apâ*d*akhshâhtar).

14\. In short (aê-mar) <span id="fr_1793"></span>[2](#fn_1781.md),
Ahyâ-yâsâ is as (pavan) <span id="fr_1794"></span>[3](#fn_1782.md)
Aûharmazd and the righteous man, Khshmaibyâ as Vohûman and cattle,
A*d*-tâ-vakhshyâ as Ar*d*avahi*s*t and fire, Tâ-v*e*-urvâtâ as
Shatvaîrô <span id="fr_1795"></span>[4](#fn_1783.md) and metal, the
*Hv*aêtumaithi as the Gâtha of Spendarma*d* and the earth, Yatha-âi*s*
as Horvada*d* and water, and Yâ-*s*kyaothanâ as Amerôda*d* and plants.

15\. The progress which is in <span id="fr_1796"></span>[5](#fn_1784.md)
the Ahunavaiti Gâtha the house-rulers should carry on; that which is in
the U*s*tavaiti Gâtha the village-rulers should carry on; that which is
in the Spe*n*tâ-mainyû <span id="fr_1797"></span>[6](#fn_1785.md) Gâtha the
tribe-rulers should carry on; that which is in the Vohû-khshathra Gâtha
the province-rulers should carry on; that which is in the
Vahi*s*tô-i*s*ti Gathâ the supreme Zaratû*s*ts should carry on, and

<span id="page_360">p. 360</span>

that which is in the Yasna, which is the place of righteous
blessing <span id="fr_1798"></span>[1](#fn_1786.md), these four classes
themselves should carry on.

16\. Of the Yasna *of seven chapters* (Yas. XXXV-XLI, 17) the beginning
section (kar*d*akŏ) *has* nine stanzas; and its beginning <span
id="fr_1799"></span>[2](#fn_1787) is Humatanãm (Yas. XXXV, 4.md), and its
end is Humatanãm (Yas. XLI, 17 supl.)

17\. The six stanzas of Ahyâ-thwâ-âthrô (Yas, XXXVI) are owing to the
six hot ordeals (var) which, in the Hûspâram *Nask* <span
id="fr_1800"></span>[3](#fn_1788.md), are effected by *k*athrayâim
âthraiãm <span id="fr_1801"></span>[4](#fn_1789.md).

18\. The five stanzas of Ithâ-â*d*-yazamaidê (Yas. XXXVII) are
thanksgiving and praise for the production of the good creations by
Aûharmazd.

19\. The five stanzas of Imãm-âa*d*-zãm (Yas. XXXVIII) are owing to
those five comforts and five discomforts of the earth, which, it is
declared in the third fargar*d* in the Vendidad <span
id="fr_1802"></span>[5](#fn_1790.md) are accomplished

<span id="page_361">p. 361</span>

thus:—'The first comfort of the earth is from the land on which a
righteous man walks forth; the second is when they shall make the
dwelling of the good and fires upon it; the third is when they sow corn
upon it, and shall take heed of dead matter; the fourth is when all
beasts *of burden* are born upon it; the fifth is when every beast *of
burden* is on it <span id="fr_1803"></span>[1](#fn_1791.md); and its first
discomfort is from the Arezûr ridge <span
id="fr_1804"></span>[2](#fn_1792.md) and the gate of hell; the second is
when they dig <span id="fr_1805"></span>[3](#fn_1793.md) it up *for* a dead
*body*; the third is when *one* constructs a depository *for the dead*
(khazân) <span id="fr_1806"></span>[4](#fn_1794.md) upon it; the fourth is
from the holes of its noxious creatures; the fifth is when they shall
forsake a man in affliction (var*d*akîh) upon it, who is righteous.'

20\. The five stanzas of Ithâ (Yas. XXXIX) are just as those which *go*
before.

21\. The four stanzas of Âhû-a*d*-paiti (Yas. XL) are about the benefit
(ar*g*-hômandîh) which is on account of water, earth, plants, and
animals.

22\. The six stanzas of Stûtô-garô (Yas. XLI, 117), the two repetitions
of Humatanãm (Yas. XX XV, 4-6), *and* the three repetitions of
Hukhshathrôtemâi (Yas. XXXV, 13-15) are on account of the existence of
the sons of Zaratû*s*t <span id="fr_1807"></span>[5](#fn_1795.md).

<span id="page_362">p. 362</span>

23\. The two repetitions of Ashahyâ-âa*d*-sairi <span
id="fr_1808"></span>[1](#fn_1796) (Yas. XXXV, 22, 23.md) are for the
laudation of righteousness and the destruction of the fiend. 24. The two
repetitions of YêNhê-hâtãm <span id="fr_1809"></span>[2](#fn_1797.md) are
for the laudation of Aûharmazd and the archangels, and the destruction
of the evil spirit and the miscreations (vishû*d*akân). 25. *The two
repetitions of* <span id="fr_1810"></span>[3](#fn_1798.md)
Thwôistaotaras*k*â, (Yas. XLI, 12-14) are for the laudation of
ceremonial worship (ya*z*i*s*nŏ) and the *sacred* feast (mâzd).

26\. The two repetitions of Âtarem*k*a (Visp. XIX, 1-8) <span
id="fr_1811"></span>[4](#fn_1799.md) are for the laudation of the Frôbâk
fire and the fire Vâzi*s*t <span id="fr_1812"></span>[5](#fn_1800.md).

27\. Of the sixteen stanzas of the U*s*tavaiti *chapter* (Yas.
XLII) <span id="fr_1813"></span>[6](#fn_1801.md) it is related just as
about the *Hv*aêtumaithi *chapter* <span
id="fr_1814"></span>[7](#fn_1802.md).

<span id="page_363">p. 363</span>

28\. The twenty stanzas of Ta*d*-thwâ-peresâ (Yas. XLIII) are the twenty
judgments (dâ*d*istân) between the beneficent spirit and the evil
spirit; and for this *reason* they should every time utter
Ta*d*-thwâ-peresâ again <span id="fr_1815"></span>[1](#fn_1803.md), because
they should utter the original judgment again, and the twentieth time
the evil spirit becomes confounded.

29\. The eleven stanzas of A*d*-fravakhshyâ (Yas. XLIV) are made up from
the six chieftainships <span id="fr_1816"></span>[2](#fn_1804.md) and the
five accomplishments (farhâng) owing to religion; one is thus, not to do
unto others <span id="fr_1817"></span>[3](#fn_1805.md) all that which is
not well for one's self; the second is to understand fully *what* is
well-done and not-well-done; the third is to turn from the vile and
their conversation (andarag-gûftanŏ); the fourth is to confess *one's*
failings to the high-priests, and let them bring the whip; the fifth is
not to neglect the season-festivals at *their proper* hour (dên hâsar),
*nor* the other things which go to the bridge <span
id="fr_1818"></span>[4](#fn_1806.md); and the six chieftainships are not
his property who has not these

<span id="page_364">p. 364</span>

five accomplishments, and he is not fit even for teaching.

30\. The nineteen stanzas of Kãm-nemôi-zãm (Yas. XLV) are for this
reason, that every one may so persevere in his own duty
(khve*s*akânîh) <span id="fr_1819"></span>[1](#fn_1807.md), that while
those are our nineteen propitiations (aû*s*ôfrî*d*) <span
id="fr_1820"></span>[2](#fn_1808.md), which it says in the Sakâ*d*ûm
*Nask* <span id="fr_1821"></span>[3](#fn_1809.md) should be my own, the
strength and power of the angels shall become more considerable, and the
destroyer more perishable.

31\. The U*s*tavaiti Gâtha is a Gâtha (gâs) of four chapters <span
id="fr_1822"></span>[4](#fn_1810), and each stanza of five lines (gâs.md),
except Hê*k*a*d*-aspâ-vakhshyâ (Yas. XLV, 15) <span
id="fr_1823"></span>[5](#fn_1811.md). 32. The two repetitions of
U*s*tâ-ahmâi (Yas. XLII, 1) <span id="fr_1824"></span>[6](#fn_1812.md) are,
one *as* a retention *and* embrace of Aûharmazd, and one *as* a
destruction of the fiends; *and* U*s*ta-Ahurem-mazdãm (Visp. XXI,
1-5) <span id="fr_1825"></span>[7](#fn_1813.md) *in* like manner.

33\. Spe*n*ta-mainyû (Yas. XLVI) *has* six stanzas, Yêzî-adâi*s* (Yas.
XLVII) twelve stanzas, A*d*-mâ-yavâ (Yas. XLVIII) twelve stanzas, *and*
Ka*d*-môi-urvâ (Yas. XLIX) eleven stanzas. 34. The Spe*n*tâ-mainyû Gâtha
is a Gâtha of four chapters <span id="fr_1826"></span>[8](#fn_1814.md), and

<span id="page_365">p. 365</span>

each stanza of four lines; it is made up from the five chieftainships
and four classes <span id="fr_1827"></span>[1](#fn_1815.md). 35. The two
repetitions of Spe*n*tâ-mainyû (Yas. XLVI, 1) <span
id="fr_1828"></span>[2](#fn_1816.md) are, one *for* the laudation of the
beneficent spirit (spendamat), and one for that of the earth <span
id="fr_1829"></span>[3](#fn_1817.md).

36\. One Spe*n*tem-Ahurem-mazdãm (Visp. XXII, 1-11) <span
id="fr_1830"></span>[4](#fn_1818.md) is the laudation of the creatures of
the beneficent spirit, and one is the destruction of the creatures of
the evil spirit.

37\. The twenty-two stanzas of the Vohû-khshathra Gâtha (Yas. L) are
those twenty-two judgments which are lodging within judges, as written
above <span id="fr_1831"></span>[5](#fn_1819.md). 38. The two repetitions
of Vohû-khshathrem (Yas. L, 1) <span id="fr_1832"></span>[6](#fn_1820.md)
are, one the laudation of living (zîndakîh), and one of the supreme
Zaratû*s*t.

39\. One Vohû-khshathrem yazamaidê (Visp. XXIII, 1-9) <span
id="fr_1833"></span>[7](#fn_1821.md) is for the laudation of
Shatvaîrô <span id="fr_1834"></span>[8](#fn_1822.md), and one of metal. 40.
The two repetitions of

<span id="page_366">p. 366</span>

<span class="contnote">\[paragraph continues\]</span> Avi-apâm (Visp.
XXIV, 1-12) <span id="fr_1835"></span>[1](#fn_1823.md) are, one for the
laudation of waters, and one of plants.

41\. The nine stanzas of the Vahi*s*tôi*s*ti (Yas. LII) are on account
of those nine things which are <span id="fr_1836"></span>[2](#fn_1824.md) .
. . the supreme Zaratû*s*tship lodging in the supreme Zaratû*s*ts, the
source of fountains, the bridge *over* waters, and even the navigable
river, the righteous man, and the righteous woman. 42. And *it is* a
Gâtha of one chapter, *and* each stanza of four lines, except
Ithâ-î-haithyâ-narô (Yas. LII, 6) <span
id="fr_1837"></span>[3](#fn_1825.md), for *there* is always one lord and
sovereign in the world. 43. And those four lines are for this *reason*,
because *it* is declared: *k*athru*s* hamay*a*u khshapô dahmayâ*d* parô
âfritôi*d* <span id="fr_1838"></span>[4](#fn_1826.md), 'four times every
night is the "blessing of the holy" (Yas. LIX),' and three *times*
Srôsh <span id="fr_1839"></span>[5](#fn_1827.md), twice Bûshâsp <span
id="fr_1840"></span>[6](#fn_1828.md), and once Aêshm <span
id="fr_1841"></span>[7](#fn_1829.md) will come

<span id="page_367">p. 367</span>

to the material world. 44. And the five *lines* of that one *stanza*
(Yas. LII, 6) are for this *reason*, because the assistants of the
supreme Zaratû*s*t are five, the house-ruler, the village-ruler, the
tribe-ruler, the province-ruler, and she even who is his own wife
(nârîk) <span id="fr_1842"></span>[1](#fn_1830.md). 45. The two repetitions
of Vahi*s*tâ-î*s*tis (Yas. LII, 1) <span
id="fr_1843"></span>[2](#fn_1831.md) are, one *for* the laudation of
sovereigns, and one for the laudation of peace (pa*d*mân).

46\. The two repetitions of Vahi*s*tem-Ahurem-mazdãm (Visp. XXVI) <span
id="fr_1844"></span>[3](#fn_1832.md) are, one *for* the laudation of
Aûharmazd and the archangels, and one for the destruction of the fiends.
47. The four repetitions of the Airyamana (Yas. LIII) <span
id="fr_1845"></span>[4](#fn_1833.md) are for the existence of more
submission (aîrmânîh) in the house, village, tribe, and province. 48.
The four repetitions of Ava*d*-mi*z*dem (Visp. XXVII) are for the
healing of those <span id="fr_1846"></span>[5](#fn_1834.md) *who* dwell in
the house, village, tribe, and province.

49\. The section (kar*d*akŏ) whose beginning is Ta*d*-sôidhi*s* (Yas.
LVII, 1-9) <span id="fr_1847"></span>[6](#fn_1835.md) is, for the
completion

<span id="page_368">p. 368</span>

of the Gâthas, taught as *pertaining*, to the Gâthas (gâsânîk *k*â*s*t).

50\. The beginning of the Gâthas is Ahyâ-yâsâ (Yas. XXVIII, 1), and
their end is drigavê vahyô (Yas. LII, 9, end); and *there* are 278
stanzas, 1016 lines, 5567 words (vâ*k*ak), 9999 mârîk, and 16,554
khûr*d*ak <span id="fr_1848"></span>[1](#fn_1836.md). 51. For the lines and
stanzas of the Gâthas *were* collected by us, and were:—one hundred
stanzas of the Ahunavaiti Gâtha (Yas. XXVIII-XXXIV), of which each
stanza is three lines; forty stanzas of the Yasna *of seven chapters*
(Yas. XXXV-XLI, 17),

<span id="page_369">p. 369</span>

of which each stanza is three lines; sixty-six stanzas of the
U*s*tavaiti Gâtha (Yas. XLII-XLV), of which each stanza is five lines,
except Haê*k*a*d*-aspâ (Yas. XLV, 15), for that one is four lines;
forty-one stanzas of the Spe*n*tâ-mainyû Gâtha (Yas. XLVI-XLIX), of
which each stanza is four lines; twenty-two stanzas of the
Vohû-khshathra (Yas. L), of which each stanza is three <span
id="fr_1849"></span>[1](#fn_1837.md) lines; *and* nine stanzas of the
Vahi*s*tôi*s*ti (Yas. LII), of which each stanza is four lines, except
Ithâ-î (Yas. LII, 6), for that one is a stanza of five;—the amount of
the foregoing <span id="fr_1850"></span>[2](#fn_1838.md) is 278
stanzas <span id="fr_1851"></span>[3](#fn_1839.md).

